post_text:
Marcia Wilson, our wonderful school counselor at Garland Elementary, received the prestigious award of Utah School Counselor Association's (USCA) Rookie of the Year! Hilary Emmer, USCA President, and Dan Gundmunson, Vice-President Elect, presented the award to Marcia today at Garland Elementary. We want to express our congratulations to her and the amazing work she does. Marcia will be participating in a panel discussion during the fall USCA conference, will receive free USCA membership for the next school year, attend the USCA conference for free, and she also received a cash award from USCA. Thank you to USCA and especially to Marcia for being such a great role model! #utschoolcounselor

First picture Dan Gundmunson, USCA VP Elect, Marcia Wilson winner of USCA award and Hilary Emmer, USCA President.

Second picture LaDawn Sorenson, Head Secretary at Garland Elementary, Marcia Wilson Counselor at Garland Elementary and Mark Johnson at Principal Garland Elementary

post_text: We are reaching out to our BESD Community in search of resources. Our Chinese DLI programs currently rely on guest teachers that come in from China to teach in our classrooms for a few years before returning to their home country. With the travel restrictions in place due to the current pandemic, there is a possibility that the guest teachers we have scheduled to come start the next school year will be delayed. We are currently looking for anyone that is qualified and interested in being a long-term substitute in a Dual Immersion Chinese class. While the need is still an uncertainty, we would like to be prepared with a way to support these classes and programs. If you or anyone you know, is interested, please contact Randy Rasmussen via email at randall.rasmussen@besd.net or by calling Adele C. Young Intermediate School at 435-734-4940.

post_text:
Dear Parents: Attached you will find three documents. Box Elder School District is using these documents to help us have consistency across the school district on how to handle these particular issues during this Covid-19 Pandemic. The information has been shared with Principals and teachers so if you have questions or concerns it would be best to deal with either the teacher or the principal of your student.

Our hope has been to continue the education of the children in our school district the best we could under the circumstances. We understand this has not been ideal and it has placed unusual pressures on you as parents. We have tried to adapt and make this situation the best it can be.

Thank you for all you have done and will continue to do. It is my complete belief that when we start school back up our professional educators will know how to access all the students’ learning and knowledge and in a short time catch them back up to where they need to be. In the meantime thank you for your help.

Sincerely,
Steven E. Carlsen
Superintendent
Box Elder School District

Brigham City Community Hospital and Cache Valley Hospital are hosting a project for young artists who would like to submit. Send a picture of your art project to the email below. Attached are a couple of submissions they have received.

Calling all young artists and their parents! Looking for an art project to do while your kids are studying online from home the next few weeks? We have an idea!

Please share your talents with us! We would love to show uplifting drawings, paintings, poems, chalk art on your driveway, words of encouragement or any other form of art with our hardworking and dedicated doctors, nurses, EMS partners and all other hospital colleagues.

Thank you in advance for helping brighten our #HealthcareHeroes days! We ask that instead of bringing anything to the hospital, you submit photos of the art in an email to nathan.miller2@hcahealthcare.com.

Coronavirus/Covid-19 Update

After listening to Governor Herbert’s and State Superintendent of Public Education Dickson’s report at noon today on KSL, Box Elder School District will remain in school. We have already started postponing after school events and any large gathering events and cancelled all school related out of state travel according to the direction from State Superintendent of Public Education Sydnee Dickson. Utah High School Activities Association has confirmed that beginning Monday, March 16, 2020, all Utah high school sponsored activities will be postponed until further notice. We are working with the Bear River Health Department and will take direction from them to determine if school closure is necessary.

shared_text:
Dr. Dave - USU Extension
October 15, 2019 at 4:00 AM ·

Anxiety! Whew, big topic to tackle for today’s Tuesday 2-minute tip! I share CPR - it can help when you’re feeding an anxious thought. And please remember that there are more things that frighten us than injure us and we suffer more in imagination than in reality.

As soon as you realize it’s a thought pattern and not you, you can begin to take more control of what happens when you have the thoughts. Hope this helps!

AND...if you haven’t read The Upward Spiral by Alex Korb, order it today! One of the very best books on anxiety and depression I’ve read! Easy read full of simple hacks to create upward spirals in your life and thinking.

August 1, 2019 at 4:51 AM ·

Listen to this:

There are scientifically proven benefits to being kind! Not only does it make you feel calmer and happier, but it improves your health. Being kind to someone releases oxytocin, which lowers blood pressure and makes you feel more kind and loving. The best part of kindness is that it’s contagious: the people you help will help others, and this spreads across a community, a city, a country, and the world.

shared_text:
Dr. Dave - USU Extension
June 17, 2019 at 5:13 PM ·

Fathers, like mothers, are pillars in the development of a child’s emotional well-being. Children look to their fathers to lay down the rules and enforce them. They also look to their fathers to provide a feeling of security, both physical and emotional. Children want to make their fathers proud, and an involved father promotes inner growth and strength. Studies have shown that when fathers are affectionate and supportive, it greatly affects a child’s cognitive and social development. It also instills an overall sense of well-being and confidence.

Dr. Dave - USU Extension
June 6, 2019 at 4:30 AM ·

Children are learning and growing in such a rapid pace. We can sit side by side with our children for only so long, then they begin exploring the technological world on their own. It's up to us to help them prepare while they are young to successfully guide through the internet safely. Setting boundaries and limits to our children's devices can also help to manage the content viewed while under parental supervision.

shared_text:
Dr. Dave - USU Extension
May 23, 2019 at 2:30 AM ·

Ready for some summer social media and expert screen tips? Let's do this! Can we control or monitor every time our children use a device? Not always. We can help motivate our kiddos to make the right decisions on what they view/avoid by preparing them beforehand & having open communication. Preparing our children when they are young can have lasting positive effects as they grow older. The effectiveness of any teaching will depend on our relationship with our children. Approach touchy topics like screen-time carefully. This will differ with young children versus teenagers, but starting on the same team with open conversations is key! More research and tech tips in the coming days...stay tuned!

Kelly Utah‎Box Elder School District
March 25, 2019 at 12:46 PM ·

Kelly Educational Staffing is currently hiring Substitute Teachers for both the Ogden and Box Elder School Districts.

In the absence of the regular classroom teacher, substitutes help students learn subject matter and skills that are required & provide meaningful instruction for students.
Job Duties Include:
-Opportunity for you to teach in grades ranging from Pre K-12.
-Create a classroom environment that is conducive to learning.
-Guides the learning process toward the achievement of curriculum goals.
-Ensures that the students are never left unattended in the classroom.

Pay: $78-$100 per day (DOE)
Flexible Schedule- Minimum Requirement of 4 days per month

Requirements:
-High School Diploma, GED or transcripts
-(2) Letters of recommendation (professional or character)
-(2) forms of ID
-Complete finger printing with the school district(s)

Perks:
-Weekly paychecks
-Training Provided
-Referral bonuses
-Flexible Schedules

February 4, 2019 at 10:09 AM ·

As our communities grow, so does the need of balancing the enrollment of our district's elementary schools. Our school board will be making a decision regarding the changing of elementary school boundaries for the upcoming school year during the March 13, 2019 school board meeting. In order to gather information and make the most informed decision, the district has scheduled several boundary change meetings. The meetings are open and there will be a scheduled public comment time on each meeting's agenda. Any of our community members, parents, and stake holders are welcome to attend.

Tuesday, February 12th at Century Elementary (6:30 PM)
Tuesday, February 19th at McKinley Elementary (6:30 PM)
Tuesday, February 26th at North Park Elementary (6:30 PM)
Tuesday, March 5th at Fielding Elementary (6:30 PM)
Monday, March 11th at Garland Elementary (6:30 PM)

post_text:
We are pleased to announce the hiring of Robert Gordon as our new BESD IT Director. He will be joining us from the Canyons School District beginning December 3rd, 2018. We like is energy, his team approach and his desire to improve student learning. He comes with 26 years of experience where he has been an elementary school teacher, worked for the Northeastern Utah Educational Services as a regional technology trainer and most recently as a ED Tech lead in the Canyons School District. We feel that his leadership strengths along with the strengths of the other 15 people in the Box Elder IT department, that our future is bright.

We want to recognize the efforts of Casey Liljenquist who has served as our interim IT director and will continue to do so until December 3rd. The efforts of all of the employees in the IT department have been exemplary as they each have taken on additional responsibilities during this transition period.

Have you ever dreamed about leaving the world behind and traveling through outer space? Now is your chance to talk with someone who plays a role in sending astronauts into orbit. A professional space rocket engineer working locally for Northrop Grumman is the scheduled speaker at Ogden School District's Astro Camp during World Space Week on October 8, 2018. There will also be interactive activities to get hands-on experience with being an astronaut. This event is for everyone, so families from Weber School District, Davis School District, and Box Elder School District are invited too. And it's free!

In celebration of Utah School Breakfast Week, Utahns Against Hunger and the Utah Breakfast Expansion Team awarded three schools with the Exemplary School Breakfast Program Award for the astounding work they have done to get their breakfast programs up and running! Help us in congratulating Highland Jr. High (Ogden School District), Mountainview Elementary (Box Elder School District), and Garland Elementary (Box Elder School District) for their exemplary breakfast programs!!

Why is school breakfast so important? Research has shown that school breakfast can:
- Decrease the risk of food insecurity
- Improve children’s overall dietary intake
- Help protect against childhood obesity
- Protect against other negative health outcomes
- Reduce students’ stress and anxiety
Source: FRAC
http://frac.org/…/increasing-breakfast-participation-to-imp…

post_text: Colleen Shaffer, Principal at Fielding Elementary, received the National Distinguished Principal Award at the Utah Association of Elementary Principals annual awards banquet. This award is given for outstanding elementary and middle school administrators for setting high standards for instruction, student achievement, character, and climate for the students, families, and staffs in their learning communities. Congratulations Colleen Shaffer!
